Large language models (LLMs) like GPT generally do not engage in continuous learning from user interactions in the traditional sense of updating their core model weights post-deployment. Instead, they rely on fixed trained parameters and use techniques like in-context learning or user embeddings to adapt responses dynamically without changing the underlying model itself.

*Why continuous learning from user interactions is limited and controlled:*

No direct fine-tuning on user inputs: Most public LLMs do not update their weights based on individual user conversations to avoid risks like data poisoning or malicious manipulation. Allowing users to influence the model‚Äôs core parameters directly would open the door to attackers implanting harmful behaviors or backdoors post-deployment.

Use of user embeddings or context: Some advanced systems personalize responses by encoding user history or preferences into embeddings that influence output generation without altering the model weights. This approach adapts behavior safely without permanent changes to the model.

Controlled updates with human oversight: When models are updated, it is usually through carefully curated datasets and supervised fine-tuning or reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), not from raw user interactions. This prevents attackers from injecting poisoned data on the fly.

Research on continual learning: New methods like Adaptive Self-Supervised Learning Strategies (ASLS) aim to personalize models on-device with minimal risk by dynamically fine-tuning based on user profiles, but these are still experimental and tightly controlled to avoid unsafe drift.

*What prevents attackers from implanting data poisoning post-deployment?*

No direct weight updates from user data: Without continuous fine-tuning on user inputs, attackers cannot implant backdoors or poisoned behaviors simply by interacting with the model.

Robust filtering and monitoring: Providers implement input filtering, anomaly detection, and safety layers to block malicious prompts or adversarial inputs that try to manipulate model behavior at inference time.

Separation of training and inference: The model‚Äôs training pipeline is isolated and secured, preventing unvetted data from leaking into training datasets.

In summary, while LLMs can adapt responses based on user context, they do not continuously learn by updating their core weights from user interactions, which effectively prevents attackers from implanting data poisoning post-deployment through normal usage.
